amics and Vulnerability to Poverty -- tChapter Twelve. Estimating Individual Vulnerability to Poverty with Pseudo-Panel Data -- tChapter Thirteen. Happiness Pays: An Analysis of Well-Being, Income, and Health Based on Russian Panel Data -- tChapter Fourteen. The Panel-of-Countries Approach to Explaining Income Inequality: An Interdisciplinary Research Agenda -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow often do working-class children obtain college degrees and then pursue professional careers? Conversely, how frequently do the children of doctors and lawyers fail to enter high status careers upon completion of their schooling? As inequalities of wealth and income have increased in industrialized nations over the past 30 years, have patterns of between-generation mobility changed? In this volume, leading sociologists and economists present original findings and conceptual arguments in response to questions like these. After assessing the range of mobility patterns observed in recent decades, the volume considers the mechanisms that generate mobility, focusing on both the training and skills that are rewarded in the labor market as well as the role of educational institutions in certifying graduates for professional positions. The volume concludes with chapters that assess the contexts of social mobility, examining the impact of macroeconomic conditions and societal levels of inequality on social and economic mobility.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh1 aAbbott, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtkinson, Anthony B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourguignon, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 